<article>
    <h1>Ja&#xAD;pan</h1>
    <h2>ONLY BUSI&#xAD;NESS TRAVEL</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201031/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-31"><time>2020-10-31</time></a>
        - <span>INSIGHT</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Ja­pan has busi­ness travel ar­range­ments with Viet­nam, Sin­ga­pore, China and South Korea. Busi­ness trav­ellers do not need to un­dergo a 14-day quar­an­tine. How­ever, they must take pre-de­par­ture and post-ar­rival Covid-19 tests, have travel in­sur­ance, present an itin­er­ary of their stay and down­load a Covid-19 con­tact trac­ing app.</p>
    <p>Ja­pan said it has started con­sul­ta­tions with Thai­land, Aus­tralia, Brunei, Hong Kong, Tai­wan and Ma­cau to set up travel bub­bles.</p>
    <p>It will also lower its travel warn­ings for 12 places – in­clud­ing Sin­ga­pore – from next month. Ja­pan re­opened its bor­ders this month to all for­eign­ers with per­mits to stay in the coun­try, but they have to self-iso­late for 14 days.</p>
    <p>Tourists are not in­cluded in this ar­range­ment.</p>


